# Reference accessed: 2026-05-31 via gh api.
#
# kiln-sprof is **Kiln's profiling wrapper** — runs
# any other kiln command under SBCL's statistical
# profiler (sb-sprof), then dumps a flat or call-
# graph report.  Kiln is "Practical Scripting in
# Common Lisp" — a multicall-binary infrastructure
# that exposes Lisp functionality as small scripts
# (analog to BusyBox: `kiln xyz` or `kiln-xyz` via
# symlink).  Pivots from R294 pillar (Pharo
# Smalltalk Clap) to **clingon — second Common Lisp
# CLI library variant in the corpus** (after R291
# `command-line-arguments` for Lem editor).  **MAJOR
# MILESTONE**: expands the Common Lisp slot in the
# cross-language CLI taxonomy from 1 to 2 variants
# — corpus now documents BOTH major CL CLI
# libraries.  Total library taxonomy: 34 variants.
#
# Critical extraction note: kiln-sprof uses **Common
# Lisp `clingon` library** at sprof.lisp:5 —
# clingon is the **modern, popular CL CLI library**
# (dnaeon/clingon), distinct from R291's
# `command-line-arguments` (older, list-data-spec
# style) and from `unix-opts`, `defcommand`, `with-
# user-abort`.  Clingon's design is heavily
# inspired by Go's `cobra` and Rust's `clap` —
# COMMAND OBJECTS hold OPTION OBJECTS, parsed via
# `cli:parse-command-line CMD ARGS` returning an
# OPAQUE PARSED-OPTIONS object.  Per-option access
# via `cli:getopt opts :key-symbol`.  Documents the
# **opaque-parsed-object-with-keyword-access
# pattern** — distinct from R291 CL `command-line-
# arguments` `handle-command-line *spec* 'handler
# :command-line args` (DISPATCH to handler) and
# R292 Erlang `getopt:parse` `{ok, {Opts, _Args}}`
# (tuple destructure).  In clingon, the parser does
# NOT dispatch — the caller `getopt`s each key by
# hand.  Corpus's **first documented opaque-
# parsed-object CLI parser**.
#
# Critical extraction note: kiln-sprof uses
# **Common Lisp `:local-nicknames` package alias**
# at sprof.lisp:3-5 — `(defpackage :kiln/scripts/
# sprof ... (:local-nicknames (:cli :clingon)))` —
# the SBCL/CCL/ECL extension `:local-nicknames`
# binds the symbol `:cli` as a LOCAL ALIAS for
# `:clingon` within this package only.  Documents
# the **package-local-alias-for-CLI-namespace
# pattern** — distinct from R291 CL
# `(:command-line-arguments)` direct full-name
# reference and from Erlang `-import(proplists,
# [get_value/2])` (Erlang import).  Common Lisp's
# `:local-nicknames` is an SBCL-pioneered de-facto
# standard (now implemented across all modern CL
# implementations) that allows SHORT ALIASES
# without polluting the global namespace.  Corpus's
# **first documented local-nicknames CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: kiln-sprof uses **kind-
# keyword as `make-option` first argument** at
# sprof.lisp:16/23/29/36/43/49/56/62/69 — every
# `cli:make-option` call's FIRST positional
# argument is a TYPE KEYWORD: `:flag` (boolean),
# `:choice` (enumerated), `:integer`, `:string`.
# Followed by `:long-name`, `:short-name`,
# `:initial-value`, `:key`, `:description` keyword
# arguments.  Documents the **type-keyword-as-
# first-positional pattern** — distinct from R291
# CL `command-line-arguments` plist-style
# `(("name" #\h) :type STRING :optional t)` (type
# is a NAMED kwarg) and R292 Erlang 5-tuple
# `{Name, Short, Long, ArgSpec, Help}` (type is
# 4th positional with optional `{Type, Default}`
# tuple).  Clingon's kind keyword resolves to a
# CLOS CLASS (`clingon.options:option-flag`,
# `clingon.options:option-choice`, etc.) at
# `make-option` time via `find-class` dispatch.
# Corpus's **first documented kind-keyword-
# dispatched CLI option**.
#
# Critical extraction note: kiln-sprof uses **CLOS-
# class-backed `:choice` option type with item
# enumeration** at sprof.lisp:29-35/36-42/62-68/
# 69-75 — four `:choice` options enumerate their
# legal values via `:items '("flat" "graph")`.
# Documents the **enumerated-items choice
# pattern** — distinct from R285 Lua argparse
# `:choices{"a","b"}` builder, R277 Kotlin clikt
# `.choice("a", "b")`, R276 Java picocli
# `@Parameters(completionCandidates =
# MyCandidates.class)`.  Clingon validates against
# the items list at parse time and emits a clear
# error message listing legal values.  TWO Common
# Lisp CLI variants now demonstrate choice
# enumeration (R291 CL had `:type X` typed but no
# choice enumeration; R295 clingon adds explicit
# `:choice :items '(...)`).
#
# Critical extraction note: kiln-sprof uses **lazy
# default referencing host special variable** at
# sprof.lisp:46/59 — `:initial-value
# sb-sprof:*max-samples*` and `:initial-value
# (princ-to-string sb-sprof:*sample-interval*)`.
# The DEFAULT for `--max-samples` is the CURRENT
# VALUE of SBCL's `sb-sprof:*max-samples*` special
# variable AT LOAD TIME of the script — NOT a
# literal.  Same for `--sample-interval` (converted
# to string via `princ-to-string`).  Documents the
# **host-variable-as-default pattern** — distinct
# from R294 Pharo lazy block default (re-evaluated
# at parse time), R285 Lua argparse `:default(8080)`
# (literal), and R287 Nim parseopt manual default
# assignment.  Clingon defaults are EVALUATED ONCE
# at `make-option` time and captured.  Plus the
# TODO comment at line 55 ("TODO Float class.")
# documents that clingon LACKS a `:float` option
# type — the developer worked around by using
# `:string` and parsing manually via `parse-float`
# at line 88.  Documents both **upstream
# limitation-noted-in-comment** and **string-as-
# float-stand-in** patterns.
#
# Critical extraction note: kiln-sprof uses **`(def
# command ...)` global binding for command spec**
# at sprof.lisp:77-80 — `def` here is the
# `serapeum:def` macro (NOT standard `defparameter`
# or `defvar`).  `(def command (cli:make-command
# :name "kiln-sprof" :options options))` binds
# `command` at COMPILE TIME to the command object.
# Documents the **module-level command-object
# binding pattern** — distinct from R291 CL
# `defparameter *command-line-spec*` (special
# variable convention with earmuffs) and from R294
# Pharo class-side `commandSpecification` method.
# Clingon convention is `def command` (no earmuffs)
# because the command is NOT meant to be
# dynamically rebound at runtime.
#
# Hunt-skip notes: skipped `_kiln` itself (would
# cover the broader multicall-binary entry point;
# but each kiln subscript has its OWN clingon spec
# living in scripts/<name>.lisp — the `kiln`
# top-level dispatches based on argv[1], so a full
# `_kiln` would need to enumerate scripts/* AND
# follow each one's clingon spec; deferred until a
# follow-up round).  Probed `lisp-chat-admin`
# (ryukinix/lisp-chat — IRC-style chat tool,
# unmaintained, niche), `ocicl` (templates/cli/src/
# main.lisp is a TEMPLATE not real CLI; ocicl
# src/ocicl.lisp does NOT use clingon despite
# repository association), `kiln-sprof` chosen as
# focused single-binary target: complete clingon
# spec in one self-contained file with all major
# clingon kinds (`:flag`, `:choice`, `:integer`,
# `:string`) represented, host-variable defaults,
# AND a TODO comment marking an upstream
# limitation — rare documentation gold.  `ciel`
# (CIEL Common Lisp REPL) already in corpus from
# unrelated AOSC-Dev/ciel-rs Rust lineage — no
# conflict but distinct tool.

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line

# 9 flags decoded source-direct from sprof.lisp:
# 14-75 (clingon :options list).
_arguments -s -S \
  '(-A --all-threads)'{-A,--all-threads}'[profile all threads (default: true)]' \
  '--loop[profile in a loop (default: false)]' \
  '--report=[report style (default: flat)]:style:(flat graph)' \
  '--mode=[profiling mode (default: cpu)]:mode:(cpu alloc time)' \
  '--max-samples=[maximum number of samples (default: SBCL sb-sprof:*max-samples*)]:n:' \
  '(-o --output)'{-o,--output}'=[output file ("-" or absent = stdout)]:file:_files' \
  '--sample-interval=[sample interval seconds (default: SBCL sb-sprof:*sample-interval*; parsed as float at runtime)]:seconds:' \
  '--sort-by=[flat-report sort key (default: samples)]:key:(samples cumulative-samples)' \
  '--sort-order=[flat-report sort order (default: descending)]:order:(descending ascending)' \
  '--help[show kiln-sprof help]' \
  '*: :_command_names -e'
